# That part of a person's life that is directly concerned with [[sexual]] activity.
#* '''1900''' January 27, [[w:Swami Vivekananda|Swami Vivekananda]], ''My Life And Mission'', in ''[[s:The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda/Volume 8/Lectures And Discourses/My Life And Mission|The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda]]'', Volume 8: Lectures And Discourses,
#*: But I cannot live the '''sex life''', although I have married you.
#* '''1918''', [[w:Marie Stopes|Marie Stopes]], ''[[s:Married Love/Chapter 8|Married Love]]'', 8,
#*: It not infrequently happens that after a love-marriage and some years of what is considered happiness, the man or woman may withdraw from the '''sex-life''', often looking down upon it, and considering that they have reached a higher plane by so doing. But such people seldom ask themselves if, while they lived it, they reached the highest possible level of the '''sex-life'''.
#* {{RQ:Lawrence Women in Love|chapter=XXIII|passage=Do you think I don't know the foulness of your '''sex life'''—and her's?—I do.}}
#* '''1922''', Henry Stanton, ''[[s:Sex/Chapter X|Sex: Avoided Subjects Discussed in Plain English]]'', Chapter X,
#*: {{quote|en|In the human animal, speaking in general, these feelings of sympathy (love) and duty are strongly developed in the family connection; that is, they are developed with special strength in those who are most intimately united in '''sex life''', in husband and wife and in children.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Steven Mithen|title=When We Were Nicer|work=London Review of Books|date=2008-01-24|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v30/n02/steven-mithen/when-we-were-nicer|volume=30|issue=02|issn=0260-9592|passage=Have you read any good books lately? Oh and by the way, how is your '''sex life'''? According to Daniel Lord Smail activities like these are the true drivers of history.}}

